“CSRF is an attack where a malicious site tricks a user’s browser into making unauthorized requests using their authenticated session. CORS does not prevent CSRF because it only blocks access to responses, not the sending of requests. To prevent CSRF, we use SameSite cookies to restrict cookie sharing across sites and CSRF tokens to validate that requests originate from the trusted application.”



What is Cross-Site Request Forgery?

👉 CSRF is when an attacker tricks a logged-in user’s browser into sending a request to your backend without the user’s intent

🧠 Core Idea
User is authenticated (cookie/session exists)
↓
Attacker triggers request from another site
↓
Browser automatically sends cookie
↓
Backend thinks it’s a valid user
💥 Step-by-Step Attack Flow
🟢 Step 1: User logs into your app
https://bank.com

Browser stores:

sessionId=abc123
🔴 Step 2: User visits malicious site
https://evil.com
💥 Step 3: Malicious site triggers request
<form action="https://bank.com/transfer" method="POST">
  <input name="amount" value="10000" />
</form>
<script>document.forms[0].submit()</script>
🟡 Step 4: Browser sends request automatically
POST /transfer
Cookie: sessionId=abc123
Origin: https://evil.com
😨 Step 5: Backend processes it
“Valid session → allow request”

👉 Money transferred ❌

⚡ Why CSRF Works

👉 Because:

1. Browser auto-sends cookies
2. Backend trusts cookie blindly
❗ Why CORS DOES NOT STOP CSRF

👉 Even if Cross-Origin Resource Sharing is enabled:

🔥 Important Truth
CORS blocks response access, NOT request sending
What actually happens:
Request goes to backend ✅
Backend processes it ✅
Browser blocks response ❌

👉 Damage already done ❗

🔐 How to Prevent CSRF
🟢 1. SameSite Cookies
What it does
Controls when browser sends cookies
Use:
Set-Cookie: sessionId=abc123; SameSite=Strict
Effect:
Cross-site request → cookie NOT sent ❌

👉 So:

Backend receives NO session → request fails ✅
🔥 Result
Attack blocked at browser level
🟡 2. CSRF Token (MOST IMPORTANT)
🧠 Idea

👉 Only your UI knows the token

🔁 Flow
Step 1: Backend generates token
csrfToken = xyz123
Step 2: Sends to UI
API response OR
cookie (non-HttpOnly)
Step 3: UI sends it with request
POST /transfer
Cookie: sessionId=abc123
X-CSRF-Token: xyz123
Step 4: Backend validates
if (token matches) → allow
else → reject ❌
🔥 Why attacker fails

👉 Malicious site cannot:

Read csrfToken ❌

👉 So cannot send correct token

⚠️ Why BOTH are needed
Protection	Strength
SameSite	Good
CSRF Token	Strong

👉 Best practice:

Use BOTH
🧠 Final Mental Model
CORS → controls reading response
CSRF → abuses sending request
SameSite → blocks cookie sending
CSRF Token → validates request authenticity
🧾 Final Takeaway

👉
CSRF occurs because browsers automatically include authentication cookies in requests, allowing attackers to perform unauthorized actions. CORS does not prevent this because it only restricts response access. CSRF can be mitigated using SameSite cookies to block cross-site cookie sending and CSRF tokens to validate legitimate requests.

